Jewish (especially Yiddish and Hebrew) terms of endearment are warm, expressive, and often a little playful. Here are some of the most common ones you’ll hear:

💛 Yiddish Terms

Bubbeleh (בובעלע) – “Little darling” or “sweetheart” (very affectionate, often for children or loved ones)

Zeeskeit (זיסקייט) – “Sweetness” (like calling someone “sweetie”)

Tateleh / Mameleh – “Little father / little mother,” used affectionately for loved ones

Neshumeleh (נשמה’לה) – From neshama (“soul”), meaning “my little soul”

Shayna punim (שיינע פּנים) – “Beautiful face”

Mayn kind – “My child” (can be used even for adults, lovingly)

Libeleh (ליבעלע) – From libe (“love”), meaning “my dear/love”

Khokhem (חכם) – Literally “wise one,” sometimes used affectionately (or teasingly!)

💙 Hebrew Terms

Neshama (נשמה) – “Soul,” used like “my dear”

Motek (מותק) – “Sweetie” or “honey” (very common in modern Hebrew)

Chayim sheli (חיים שלי) – “My life”

Ahava sheli (אהבה שלי) – “My love”

Kapara (כפרה) – Literally “atonement,” but colloquially “my dear” or “darling” (especially in Israeli slang)

Yakar / Yakara (יקר / יקרה) – “Precious” (masculine/feminine)
Yaldati/Yaldi - "My girl/my boy"


💫 A Note on Tone

A lot of these can be:

Deeply affectionate (grandparents → grandchildren)

Playfully teasing (friends or family)

Context-dependent (tone matters a lot!)

